                    <h3 style="width:100%;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-size:16px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px;font-weight:700;color:#28121F;line-height:20px;text-transform:capitalize;letter-spacing:-0.32px;text-align:left">Nigeria&#8217;s Q4 2025 tax collection result tells two stories</h3>
                    <div style="font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;font-weight: 400;font-size:16px;line-height:25.6px;margin:0;padding-bottom:16px">
<figure style="width: 100%;padding-bottom:16px;text-align:left;margin:0">

<a href="https://techcabal.com/category/newsletters/tc-daily/">
<img decoding="async" 
     	loading="lazy" src="https://c76c7bbc41.mjedge.net/wp-content/uploads/tc/2025/09/simpsons-taxes.gif" width="100%" height="auto" style="object-fit: cover"></a>
<figcaption style="color:#808080;font-size:12px;font-family:'Helvetica Neue', Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif;line-height:19.8px;padding-top:6px;font-weight:400">Image source: Tenor</figcaption>
</figure>
                        
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0">In the fourth quarter of 2025, Nigeria&rsquo;s Value Added Tax (VAT) collections and Company Income Tax (CIT) collections dropped quarter-on-quarter, according to the country&rsquo;s Bureau of Statistics.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>People are still spending: </strong>VAT, which tracks and collects from everyday spending, <a style="text-decoration: underline;color: #b61313 !important" href="https://nairametrics.com/2026/04/08/nigerias-vat-collections-drop-to-n2-19-trillion-in-q4-2025/">reduced </a>by 3.78% to ₦2.19 trillion ($1.5 billion) from the ₦2.28 trillion ($1.65 billion) in the previous quarter. Although it declined, it shows that people are still making purchases and transactions, just a bit more cautiously.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>Companies are struggling: </strong>CIT <a style="text-decoration: underline;color: #b61313 !important" href="https://nairametrics.com/2026/04/08/nigerias-company-income-tax-collections-drop-49-8-in-q4-2025/">fell sharply</a> by 49.81% to ₦1.49 trillion ($1.08 billion) in Q4 from ₦2.96 trillion ($2.1 billion) in Q3 2025. CIT usually tracks corporate profitability and taxable earnings, and such a sharp decline suggests that companies are under a different kind of pressure, ranging from lower earnings to delayed remittances.</p>
<p style="padding:5px 0;margin:0"><strong>Why this matters: </strong>This split was happening just before Nigeria fully settled into its <a style="text-decoration: underline;color: #b61313 !important" href="https://techcabal.com/2026/02/21/nigerias-new-capital-gains-tax-sparks-foreign-vc-anxiety/">new tax regime</a> that took effect in 2026. So these numbers feel like a checkpoint about what things looked like before the rules tightened and compliance expanded. If reforms work, we might see stronger collections driven by a wider tax base and fewer quarterly drops.</p>
                    </div>
